    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1935-12-16T04:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1935-12-16T04:00:00-05:00" n="924"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d924">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.6363 Manchuria/267: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in China</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Johnson</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Peiping</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1935-12-16T17:00:00+08:00"
                            >December 16, 1935—5 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received December 16—3:50 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>231. Embassy’s 205, December 6, 7 p.m. Following telegram has been received from
                    the Consul General at Mukden: <quote rend="blockquote">
                        <p>“December 15, noon. I have received the following communication dated
                            December 13th from Minister for Foreign Affairs: <quote
                                rend="blockquote">
                                <p>‘With regard to the matter of purchasing the equipments of the
                                    three oil companies, I have discussed the subject with Mr.
                                    Hoshino and we are agreed in <pb facs="1049" n="937"
                                        xml:id="pg_937"/> the opinion that this Government is not in
                                    the position to recognize the principle of compensating the
                                    losses incurred by your oil concerns as a result of the
                                    enforcement of our national policy, although the Finance
                                    Department should endeavor to complete, as soon as possible, the
                                    investigations as to the value of the equipments and be prepared
                                    to purchase the said equipment for a reasonable price in
                                    accordance with the laws and regulations.</p>
                                <p>When the negotiation reaches a stage which requires my good
                                    offices, I shall be ready to do my best to settle the matter in
                                    a manner satisfactory to both parties.</p>
                                <p>I am, et cetera, T. Ohashi.’</p>
                            </quote>
                        </p>
                        <p>Embassy at Tokyo informed.”</p>
                    </quote>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Johnson</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
